(2472, 933, 'I think this song is a good reminder to everyone about how present God is!  Also, I think it could work as an alto solo.', 55, '2016-12-18 15:58:13'),
(2473, 14, 'I''m a big fan of GLAD arrangements so I definitely like this idea.', 58, '2016-12-20 03:25:01'),
(2474, 975, 'Oh yeah, I can definitely imagine this as a low alto solo. It''s interesting. Usually when I hear the phrase "rock bottom" I think about somebody''s state of life being at an absolute low ("Why did it take the rock bottom to make you realize?"). Here they''re using it just to describe the endless depth of God. Possibly, there''s a second meaning, that our lives never hit rock bottom when we''re focusing on God.', 62, '2016-12-20 04:41:13'),
(2475, 978, 'I think that this song is nice and upbeat and would translate to a cappella well, however I think that some non-christians may be a bit surprised by the use of "bought by your blood" and I think it would need a good blurb.', 55, '2016-12-20 15:41:56'),
(2476, 999, 'I like this one a lot! I think there''s some really cool a cappella stuff that could be done with the dense background parts.  Also, I think that the message of thriving is something that MIT students would love to hear.  Also, it may need to be raised a step or to, but this could be a low alto solo.', 55, '2016-12-20 15:45:04'),
(2477, 919, 'Echoing my previous comment-  I think it''s a gorgeous song but there''s so much terminology that I''m concerned about it as a song in our setlist.', 55, '2016-12-20 16:05:51'),
(2478, 919, 'I agree there should be a blurb if we sung this to a non-Christian audience, and if we couldn''t blurb, we probably wouldn''t sing this song at a particular gig, but I don''t think that should discount the song from the setlist completely. \r\n\r\nI think the song would be a great testament to what true worship should be and speaks against the necessity of all the fluff and flashiness that you see a lot. I think non-Christians see those kinds of things and perhaps assume that''s what worship is supposed to look like and attach some kind performance requirement to it. It''s like feeling like you need to dress nicely to go to church or have everything ''together'' before you can talk to God. This song could help point people to what actually matters, Christian or not. \r\n\r\nI think this would super-powerful to sing at churches and youth groups in Dallas. It also relates a lot to what my home church has been through (Jerk the pews and all the decorations, too, until the congregation''s few, then have revival).\r\n\r\nAnyway, this song speaks of a kind of dependency and humility and brokenness that I don''t see a lot elsewhere. Yeah, it relates a lot to xprod and what we do, but it''s not just about singing worship songs. I think the message is still very applicable to the rest of the Church and could help non-Christians better understand what we do and why we do it.\r\n\r\nAlso, Princeton''s Kindred Spirit sung this at BIDB 2015. Here''s a link to their version (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ep-MvUjmF4o).', 57, '2016-12-20 22:13:42'),
(2479, 975, 'It''s got a nice beat and love the message.', 57, '2016-12-20 22:30:22'),
(2480, 935, 'Would love to do this again! (I speak Spanish and English. Could get a Serbian translation, but I''m not a native speaker.)', 57, '2016-12-20 22:41:46'),
(2481, 979, 'Mmm, yeah, I like this. Would definitely add some nice variation.', 57, '2016-12-20 22:54:23'),
(2482, 978, 'Should all Spring Break songs be "Spring Break friendly"?', 69, '2016-12-22 02:37:48'),
(2483, 873, 'Ooh, if we do this song I want a part in writing the MIT version! ^', 69, '2016-12-22 03:19:49'),
(2484, 939, 'I can see some cool arrangement with the "Brave!" echoing in the background.', 69, '2016-12-22 03:22:13'),
